[[Marshal of the Royal Air Force]] '''William Sholto Douglas, 1st Baron Douglas of Kirtleside''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|MC|DFC}} (23 December 1893 – 29 October 1969) was a senior commander in the [[Royal Air Force]]. After serving as a pilot, then a flight commander and finally as a squadron commander during the [[First World War]], he served a flying instructor during the inter-war years before becoming Director of Staff Duties and then [[Assistant Chief of the Air Staff]] at the [[Air Ministry]].

During the [[Second World War]] Douglas clashed with other senior commanders over strategy in the [[Battle of Britain]]. Douglas argued for a more aggressive engagement with a '[[Big Wing]]' strategy i.e. using massed fighters to defend the United Kingdom against enemy bombers. He then became  [[Air Officer Commanding-in-Chief]] of [[RAF Fighter Command|Fighter Command]] in which role he was responsible for rebuilding the command's strength after the attrition of the [[Battle of Britain]], but also for bringing it on the offensive to wrest the initiative in the air from the German [[Luftwaffe]].

Douglas went on to be Air Officer Commanding in Chief of [[RAF Middle East Command]] in which role he was an advocate of [[Operation Accolade]], a planned British amphibious assault on [[Rhodes]] and the [[Dodecanese Islands]] in the [[Aegean Sea]], and was disappointed when it was abandoned. He became commander of the [[British Zone of Occupation]] in [[Germany]] after the war.

==Early life==
Born the son of Professor [[Robert Langton Douglas]] and his wife Margaret Jane Douglas (née Cannon), Douglas was educated at [[Emanuel School]], [[Tonbridge School]] and [[Lincoln College, Oxford]].<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/32876?docPos=2|title=Sholto Douglas, 1st Baron Douglas of Kirtleside|publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

==Early military career==
Douglas was commissioned as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Field Artillery]] on 15 August 1914.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28876 |date=21 August 1914 |startpage=6597|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> In January 1915, following a disagreement with his commanding officer, he transferred to the [[Royal Flying Corps]] joining [[No. 2 Squadron RAF|No. 2 Squadron]] as an observer.<ref>Douglas 1963, p. 75</ref> He soon trained as a pilot and earned [[Royal Aero Club]] certificate No 1301.<ref>Douglas 1963, p. 85</ref> Promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 9 June 1915, he became a pilot with  [[No. 14 Squadron RAF|No. 14 Squadron]] at [[Shoreham Airport|Shoreham]] in July 1915 and then transferred to [[No. 8 Squadron RAF|No. 8 Squadron]], flying [[Royal Aircraft Factory B.E.2|B.E.2c aircraft]] on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]], in August 1915.<ref name=air>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Biographies/Douglas.htm |publisher=Air of Authority – A History of RAF Organisation |title= Marshal of the Royal Air Force Lord Douglas of Kirtleside|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> Appointed a flight commander with the rank of temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in December 1915, he joined [[No. 18 Squadron RAF|No. 18 Squadron]] at [[RAF Montrose|Montrose]] in January 1916.<ref>Douglas 1963, p. 131</ref> He was awarded the [[Military Cross]] on 14 January 1916.<ref name=mc>{{London Gazette|issue=29438|date=11 January 1916 |startpage=582|endpage= |supp= yes|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

Douglas went on to be officer commanding [[No. 43 Squadron RAF|No. 43 Squadron]], flying [[Sopwith 1½ Strutter]]s on the Western Front, in April 1916 and, having been promoted to temporary [[major]] on 1 July 1916, he became then officer commanding [[No. 84 Squadron RAF|No. 84 Squadron]], flying [[Royal Aircraft Factory S.E.5|S.E.5]]s on the Western Front, in August 1917.<ref>Douglas 1963, p. 214</ref> He was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] on 8 February 1919.<ref name=dfc>{{London Gazette|city=e|issue=13400|date=11 February 1919 |startpage=796|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

After the war Douglas worked briefly for [[Handley Page]] and as a commercial pilot before rejoining the Royal Air Force in 1920 after a chance meeting with [[Hugh Trenchard, 1st Viscount Trenchard|Hugh Trenchard]].<ref name=odnb/> After being granted a permanent commission as a [[squadron leader]] on 25 March 1920,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32193 |date=14 January 1921|startpage=376|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> Douglas attended the [[RAF Staff College, Andover|RAF Staff College]] and then served as a flight instructor four years.<ref name=air/> Promoted to [[Wing commander (rank)|wing commander]] on 1 January 1925,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33007 |date=30 December 1924 |startpage=8|endpage= |supp=yes |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> he continued his work as an instructor before attending the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]] in 1927.<ref name=air/> He became station commander at [[RAF North Weald]] in January 1928 and then joined the Air Staff at Headquarters Middle East Command in [[Khartoum]] in August 1929.<ref name=air/> Promoted to [[group captain]] on 1 January 1932,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33785 |date=29 December 1931 |startpage=16|endpage= |supp=yes |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> he became an instructor at the Imperial Defence College in June 1932 and then, having been promoted to [[air commodore]] on 1 January 1935,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34176 |date=2 July 1935|startpage=4262|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> he became Director of Staff Duties at the [[Air Ministry]] on 1 January 1936.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34242 |date=14 January 1936|startpage=311|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> Promoted to [[air vice marshal]] on 1 January 1938,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34468 |date=31 December 1937 |startpage=8194|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> he went on to be [[Assistant Chief of the Air Staff]] on 17 February 1938.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34488 |date=1 March 1938 |startpage=1351|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

==Second World War==
[[File:Royal Air Force 1939-1945- Fighter Command CH4209.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Air Marshal Sir William Sholto Douglas, Commander-in-Chief Fighter Command (left) during a visit to No 61 OTU at [[Heston Aerodrome|Heston]], November 1941]]
On 22 April 1940, with the [[World War II|Second World War]] well under way, he was made [[Deputy Chief of the Air Staff]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34840 |date=30 April 1940 |startpage=2556|endpage= |supp= |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> He was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] on 11 July 1940.<ref name=cb>{{London Gazette|issue=34893 |date=9 July 1940 |startpage=4245|endpage= |supp= yes|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> During 1940, Douglas and [[Trafford Leigh-Mallory]] clashed with the head of [[No. 11 Group RAF|No. 11 Group]], [[Keith Park]], and the head of [[RAF Fighter Command|Fighter Command]], [[Hugh Dowding, 1st Baron Dowding|Hugh Dowding]], over strategy in the [[Battle of Britain]]. Douglas argued for a more aggressive engagement with a '[[Big Wing]]' strategy i.e. using massed fighters to defend the United Kingdom against enemy bombers.<ref name=odnb/> When [[Charles Portal]] was made [[Chief of the Air Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Air Staff]] in October 1940 he supported Douglas, moving Park and Dowding and appointing Douglas to replace Dowding as [[Air Officer Commanding-in-Chief]] of Fighter Command, with the temporary rank of [[air marshal]] on 25 November 1940.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35010|date=10 December 1940|startpage=6982|supp=| accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> He was advanced to [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] on 1 July 1941<ref name=kcb>{{London Gazette |issue=35204|date=27 June 1941 |startpage=3736|supp=yes| accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> and promoted to the substantive rank of air marshal on 14 April 1942.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35525|date=14 April 1942|startpage=1648|supp=| accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

At around this time Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] recommended Douglas to command the [[China Burma India Theater]] but General [[George Marshall]] refused to accept the appointment due to Douglas's well known dislike of Americans.<ref>Pogue, p. 258</ref>

As commander-in-chief of Fighter Command, Douglas was responsible for rebuilding the command's strength after the attrition of the [[Battle of Britain]], but also for bringing it on the offensive to wrest the initiative in the air from the German ''[[Luftwaffe]]''. He was therefore one of the main orchestrators of the only partially successful [[Circus offensive]] whereby large wings of fighters accompanied by bombers would take advantage of good weather to sweep over Northern France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spitfiresite.com/2010/04/1941-royal-air-force-offensive.html/3|title=1941: The Difficult Year|last=Douglas|first=Sir Sholto|publisher=Spitfire site|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

Douglas was promoted to temporary [[air chief marshal]] on 1 July 1942.<ref name=air/> In January 1943 Douglas was replaced at Fighter Command by [[Trafford Leigh-Mallory]] and was transferred to [[Egypt]], becoming Air Officer Commanding in Chief of [[RAF Middle East Command]] in January 1943.<ref>Douglas 1966, p. 179</ref> In that capacity Douglas was an advocate of [[Operation Accolade]], a planned British amphibious assault on [[Rhodes]] and the [[Dodecanese Islands]] in the [[Aegean Sea]], and was disappointed when it was abandoned.<ref name=odnb/>

[[File:The Royal Air Force during the Second World War- Personalities TR893.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Air Chief Marshal Sir William Sholto Douglas, Air Officer Commanding-in-Chief, RAF Middle East Command (left) with Air Officer Commanding Malta, Air Vice Marshal [[Keith Park|Sir Keith Park]] in the garden at HQ, Malta]]
Douglas returned to England in January 1944 to head [[Coastal Command]] during the [[Operation Overlord|invasion of Normandy]] and then, having been confirmed in the rank of air chief marshal on 6 June 1945,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=37124|date=8 June 1945 |startpage=3073|supp=yes| accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> he became Commander in Chief, British Air Forces of Occupation in July 1945.<ref>Douglas 1966, p. 290</ref> He was advanced to [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] on 1 January 1946.<ref name=gcb>{{London Gazette |issue=37407|date=28 December 1945 |startpage=5|supp=| accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

Promoted to [[marshal of the Royal Air Force]] on 1 January 1946,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37414 |date=28 December 1945 |startpage=187|endpage= |supp=yes |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> Douglas became the second commander of the [[British Zone of Occupation]] in Germany in May 1946.<ref name=air/> He was raised to the peerage as Baron Douglas of Kirtleside, of Dornock in the County of Dumfries on 17 February 1948.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=38210 |date=17 February 1948 |startpage=1127| accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p23343.htm#i233430|title=Person Page 23343| publisher=Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes, Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A., 2003, volume 1, page 842. Genealogical Books Ltd, 2003,|accessdate=2014-11-12}}</ref> Douglas retired in 1947 and became chairman of [[British European Airways|BEA]] in 1949, a post he retained until 1964. He published two volumes of autobiography, ''Years of Combat'', covering the First World War, and ''Years of Command'' covering the Second World War.<ref name=odnb/>

Douglas died in hospital in [[Northampton]] on 29 October 1969 and was buried at [[St Clement Danes]] in [[Strand, London|The Strand]] in [[London]].<ref name=odnb/>

==Family==
Lord Douglas of Kirtleside was married three times. He married firstly May Howard in October 1919. They had no children and were divorced in 1932. He married secondly Joan Leslie (née Denny) in 1933. This marriage was also childless and ended in divorce in 1952. He married thirdly Hazel Walker (née Walker) in 1955: they had one daughter.<ref name=odnb/>

